{"content":{"result":[{"rank_order":1,"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/prescriptive-guidance/latest/patterns/monitor-iam-root-user-activity.html","title":"Monitor IAM root user activity - AWS Prescriptive Guidance","context":"The document outlines a method for monitoring IAM root user activity in an AWS environment using a hub-and-spoke architecture. The root user, which has full access to all AWS resources and billing information, should be used sparingly and monitored for any activity that may indicate compromise. The pattern involves setting up CloudWatch and CloudTrail to record root user activity, an EventBridge rule to send events to a central event bus in a hub account, a Lambda function to process the events and send notifications via Amazon SNS, and the use of AWS CloudFormation and Terraform to deploy the monitoring and event-handling services. Prerequisites include permissions to deploy AWS resources, Terraform, an existing trail in each spoke account, and the hub and spoke accounts being managed by AWS Organizations. The document provides instructions for deploying the templates in the hub and spoke accounts, as well as an optional step for testing notifications. Additionally, it mentions Amazon GuardDuty as an alternative solution for monitoring root user activity. AWS services used include CloudFormation, CloudTrail, CloudWatch Logs, EventBridge, IAM, Lambda, and SNS. Other tools and services include Terraform and GitHub"},{"rank_order":2,"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/IAM/latest/UserGuide/root-user-best-practices.html","title":"Root user best practices for your AWS account - AWS Identity and Access Management","context":"The document outlines best practices for securing the root user credentials of an AWS account. The root user is the default identity with full access to all AWS resources in an account. It is recommended to avoid using the root user for everyday tasks and instead create an administrative user for regular access. The root user credentials should be kept secure and not shared with anyone except those with a strict business need. A strong, unique password and multi-factor authentication (MFA) should be used for the root user. Access keys should not be created for the root user, and multi-person approval should be used for root user sign-in wherever possible. A group email address should be used for root user credentials, and access to account recovery mechanisms should be restricted. For organizations managing multiple accounts, root user access can be centralized or secured with MFA. Preventative security controls can be set in AWS Organizations using a service control policy (SCP). Monitoring services such as Amazon CloudWatch, Amazon EventBridge, and Amazon SNS can be used to track and alert on root user activity. AWS Config, Security Hub, and Trusted Advisor can help evaluate MFA compliance for root user credentials. The document also includes information on document conventions and business use cases"},{"rank_order":3,"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/awscloudtrail/latest/userguide/cloudtrail-event-reference-aws-console-sign-in-events.html","title":"AWS Management Console sign-in events - AWS CloudTrail","context":"The document provides detailed information about AWS Management Console sign-in events logged by AWS CloudTrail. It covers the following key points:

- CloudTrail logs sign-in attempts to the AWS Management Console, AWS Discussion Forums, and AWS Support Center for IAM users, root users, and federated users.
- Users can set up AWS User Notifications to receive notifications about CloudTrail sign-in events through various channels like email, chat, and mobile app.
- The recorded region for a "ConsoleLogin" event varies based on the user type and the sign-in endpoint used.
- The document provides example event records for successful and unsuccessful sign-ins by IAM users, root users, and federated users, including scenarios with and without multi-factor authentication (MFA).
- For IAM users, the examples show events for successful sign-in without MFA, successful sign-in with MFA, unsuccessful sign-in, sign-in process checking for MFA with a single device type, and sign-in process checking for MFA with multiple device types.
- For root users, the examples show events for successful sign-in without MFA, successful sign-in with MFA, unsuccessful sign-in, MFA change, and password change.
- For federated users, the examples show events for a successful sign-in without MFA and a federation encryption request"},{"rank_order":4,"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/whitepapers/latest/aws-security-incident-response-guide/logging-and-events.html","title":"Logging and events - AWS Security Incident Response Guide","context":"The document discusses various AWS services related to logging and events for enhancing security and monitoring in AWS environments. AWS CloudTrail is a service that logs and monitors account activity across AWS services, including management and data plane operations. Amazon CloudWatch Events delivers real-time notifications for operational changes and can route events to targets for automated responses. AWS Config enables assessment, auditing, and evaluation of AWS resource configurations. Amazon S3 access logs record every upload, download, and modification to data in an S3 bucket. Amazon CloudWatch Logs monitors and accesses log files from various sources. Amazon VPC Flow Logs captures IP traffic information for network interfaces in VPCs. AWS WAF logs record web requests inspected by the service, and Route53 Resolver query logs log DNS queries made by resources within Amazon VPC. The document also mentions other AWS services with logging and monitoring capabilities"},{"rank_order":5,"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/partner-central/latest/APIReference/logging-account.html","title":"Logging the AWS Partner Central Account API - AWS Partner Central","context":"The AWS Partner Central Account API is integrated with AWS CloudTrail, which records all API calls as events. These events can be logged and delivered as log files to an Amazon S3 bucket. Each log file may contain one or more events. The following is an example of a CloudTrail log entry for the `CreatePartner` action on AWS Partner Central Account API:

